"A DNA virus with high risk of chronic infection in neonates","A DNA virus that requires co-infection to cause cirrhosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis B is a \u003Cstrong\u003EDNA virus\u003C/strong\u003E belonging to the Hepadnaviridae family. The risk of chronic infection varies significantly with age at acquisition. When infection occurs in neonates, there is a 90% risk of developing chronic infection. In contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Eadult infection has less than 5% risk of becoming chronic\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA ribonucleic acid virus that causes acute liver inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - Hepatitis B is a DNA virus, not an RNA virus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA DNA virus that primarily affects immunocompromised hosts\u003C/strong\u003E - Hepatitis B can infect both immunocompetent and immunocompromised individuals\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA DNA virus with high risk of chronic infection in adults\u003C/strong\u003E - Adult infection actually has a low risk of chronicity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA DNA virus that requires co-infection to cause cirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Hepatitis B can cause cirrhosis independently\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe age-dependent risk of chronic infection is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPerinatal: 90% become chronic carriers\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAges one to five years: 20-50% become chronic carriers\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAdults: Less than 5% become chronic carriers\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatitis B virus is a DNA virus of the Hepadnaviridae family","Age of acquisition strongly influences the natural history of hepatitis B infection","Perinatal hepatitis B infection has a 90% risk of becoming chronic, while adult infection has less than 5% risk"],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436","Lok AS, Pawlotsky JM. Viral hepatitis at a crossroad. Gastroenterology. 2012 May;142(6):1261-3. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2012.03.007. PMID: 22537431","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scienc","Song JE, Kim DY. Diagnosis of hepatitis B. Ann Transl Med. 2016 Sep;4(18):338. doi: 10.21037/atm.2016.09.11. PMID: 27761442; PMCID: PMC5066055"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15357"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T20:14:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T20:17:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8048"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68535"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"